# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tokenization-nlp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] In computing, **byte-pair encoding** (**BPE**), or **digram coding**, is an algorithm, first described in 1994 by Philip Gage, for encoding strings of text into smaller strings by creating and using a translation table.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] A slightly modified version of the algorithm is used in large language model tokenizers.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The original version of the algorithm focused on compression.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] It replaces the highest-frequency pair of bytes with a new byte that was not contained in the initial dataset.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] A lookup table of the replacements is required to rebuild the initial dataset.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The modified version builds "tokens" (units of recognition) that match varying amounts of source text, from single characters (including single digits or single punctuation marks) to whole words (even long compound words).
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The original BPE algorithm operates by iteratively replacing the most common contiguous sequences of characters in a target text with unused 'placeholder' bytes.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The iteration ends when no sequences can be found, leaving the target text effectively compressed.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] Decompression can be performed by reversing this process, querying known placeholder terms against their corresponding denoted sequence, using a lookup table.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] In the original paper, this lookup table is encoded and stored alongside the compressed text.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The byte pair "aa" occurs most often, so it will be replaced by a byte that is not used in the data, such as "Z".
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The only literal byte pair left occurs only once, and the encoding might stop here.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] This data cannot be compressed further by byte-pair encoding because there are no pairs of bytes that occur more than once.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] To decompress the data, simply perform the replacements in the reverse order.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The original BPE algorithm is modified for use in language modeling, especially for large language models based on neural networks.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] Compared to the original BPE, the modified BPE does not aim to maximally compress text, but rather, to encode plaintext into "tokens", which are natural numbers.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] All the unique tokens found in a corpus are listed in a token vocabulary.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The token vocabulary can also include some other special tokens, relative to the use case.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The size of the token vocabulary, in the case of GPT-3.5 and GPT-4, is 100258 (100000 from BPE algorithm and 258 included as special tokens).
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] The modified tokenization algorithm initially treats the set of unique characters as 1-character-long n-grams (the initial tokens).
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] Then, successively, the most frequent pair of adjacent tokens is merged into a new, longer n-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by this new token.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] This is repeated until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] Note that new words can always be constructed from final vocabulary tokens and initial-set characters.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] This modified BPE approach has been extended from spoken language to sign language in recent years.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] Suppose we are encoding the previous example of "aaabdaaabac", with a specified vocabulary size of 6, then it would first be encoded as "0, 0, 0, 1, 2, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 3" with a vocabulary of "a=0, b=1, d=2, c=3".
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] So far this is essentially the same as before.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] However, if we only had specified a vocabulary size of 5, then the process would stop at vocabulary "a=0, b=1, d=2, c=3, aa=4", so that the example would be encoded as "4, 0, 1, 2, 4, 0, 1, 0, 3".
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] Conversely, if we had specified a vocabulary size of 8, then it would be encoded as "7, 6, 0, 3", with a vocabulary of "a=0, b=1, d=2, c=3, aa=4, ab=5, aaab=6, aaabd=7".
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] This is not maximally compressed, because modified BPE does not aim for maximum compression.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] Instead, it aims for an encoding that is efficient and practical for language model training.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] In the above example, the output of the BPE is a vocabulary, which can be used to encode any text that is written with the letters "abcd".
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] It will not be able to encode text containing other symbols, such as "no".
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] Even giving each of the 26 letters an entry in the vocabulary, since there are many languages in the world using many different scripts, inevitably some symbols would be unencodable by such a vocabulary.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] One solution is to replace any unencodable symbol with a special symbol named UNK ("unknown").
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] It simply converts the text into UTF-8 first, and treat it as a stream of bytes.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] This guarantees that any text encoded in UTF-8 can be encoded by the BPE.
[src:tokenization-nlp/byte-pair-encoding] This has been used in BERT-like models like RoBERTa, BART, and DeBERTa, and GPT-like models like GPT-2.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] A **language model** is a computational model that predicts sequences in natural language.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Large language models (LLMs), currently their most advanced form as of 2026, are predominantly based on transformers trained on larger datasets (frequently using texts scraped from the public internet).
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] They have superseded recurrent neural network-based models, which had previously superseded the purely statistical models, such as the word *n*-gram language model.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Noam Chomsky did pioneering work on language models in the 1950s by developing a theory of formal grammars.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] In 1980, statistical approaches were explored and found to be more useful for many purposes than rule-based formal grammars.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Discrete representations like word *n*-gram language models, with probabilities for discrete combinations of words, made significant advances.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] In the 2000s, continuous representations for words, such as word embeddings, began to replace discrete representations.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes a word’s meaning such that words closer in vector space are similar in meaning and common relationships between words, such as plurality or gender, are preserved.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] A word *n*-gram language model is a statistical model of language which calculates the probability of the next word in a sequence from a fixed size window of previous words.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] If one previous word is considered, it is a bigram model; if two words, a trigram model; if *n* − 1 words, an *n*-gram model.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Special tokens are introduced to denote the start and end of a sentence $\langle s\rangle$ and $\langle /s\rangle$ .
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] To prevent a zero probability being assigned to unseen words, the probability of each seen word is slightly lowered to make room for the unseen words in a given corpus.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] To achieve this, various smoothing methods are used, from simple "add-one" smoothing (assigning a count of 1 to unseen *n*-grams, as an uninformative prior) to more sophisticated techniques, such as Good–Turing discounting or back-off models.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Word *n-*gram models have largely been superseded by recurrent neural network–based models, which in turn have been superseded by Transformer-based models often referred to as large language models.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Maximum entropy language models encode the relationship between a word and the *n*-gram history using feature functions.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] where $Z(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m-1})$ is the partition function, a is the parameter vector, and $f(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m})$ is the feature function.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] In the simplest case, the feature function is just an indicator of the presence of a certain *n*-gram.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] It is helpful to use a prior on a or some form of regularization.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] The log-bilinear model is another example of an exponential language model.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Skip-gram language model is an attempt at overcoming the data sparsity problem that the preceding model (i.e. word *n*-gram language model) faced.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Words represented in an embedding vector were not necessarily consecutive anymore, but could leave gaps that are *skipped* over (thus the name "skip-gram").
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Formally, a k-skip-n-gram is a length-n subsequence where the components occur at distance at most k from each other.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] In skip-gram model, semantic relations between words are represented by linear combinations, capturing a form of compositionality.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] where ≈ is made precise by stipulating that its right-hand side must be the nearest neighbor of the value of the left-hand side.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Continuous representations or embeddings of words are produced in recurrent neural network-based language models (known also as *continuous space language models*).
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Such continuous space embeddings help to alleviate the curse of dimensionality, which is the consequence of the number of possible sequences of words increasing exponentially with the size of the vocabulary, further causing a data sparsity problem.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Neural networks avoid this problem by representing words as non-linear combinations of weights in a neural net.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] A large language model (LLM) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Although sometimes matching human performance, it is not clear whether they are plausible cognitive models.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] At least for recurrent neural networks, it has been shown that they sometimes learn patterns that humans do not, but fail to learn patterns that humans typically do.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Evaluation of the quality of language models is mostly done by comparison to human created sample benchmarks created from typical language-oriented tasks.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Other, less established, quality tests examine the intrinsic character of a language model or compare two such models.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Since language models are typically intended to be dynamic and to learn from data they see, some proposed models investigate the rate of learning, e.g., through inspection of learning curves.
[src:tokenization-nlp/language-model] Various data sets have been developed for use in evaluating language processing systems.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A rule-based program, performing lexical tokenization, is called *tokenizer*, or *scanner*, although *scanner* is also a term for the first stage of a lexer.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexer forms the first phase of a compiler frontend in processing.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexers and parsers are most often used for compilers, but can be used for other computer language tools, such as prettyprinters or linters.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexing can be divided into two stages: the *scanning*, which segments the input string into syntactic units called *lexemes* and categorizes these into token classes, and the *evaluating*, which converts lexemes into processed values.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexers are generally quite simple, with most of the complexity deferred to the syntactic analysis or semantic analysis phases, and can often be generated by a lexer generator, notably lex or derivatives.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, lexers can sometimes include some complexity, such as phrase structure processing to make input easier and simplify the parser, and may be written partly or fully by hand, either to support more features or for performance.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing is not equal to what is called lexeme in linguistics.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing can be equal to the linguistic equivalent only in analytic languages, such as English, but not in highly synthetic languages, such as fusional languages.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] What is called a lexeme in rule-based natural language processing is more similar to what is called a word in linguistics (not to be confused with a word in computer architecture), although in some cases it may be more similar to a morpheme.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A *lexical token* is a string with an assigned and thus identified meaning, in contrast to the probabilistic token used in large language models.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexical token consists of a *token name* and an optional *token value*.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The token name is a category of a rule-based lexical unit.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A token name is what might be termed a part of speech in linguistics.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] the string is not implicitly segmented on spaces, as a natural language speaker would do.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The raw input, the 43 characters, must be explicitly split into the 9 tokens with a given space delimiter (i.e., matching the string `" "` or regular expression `/\s{1}/`).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] When a token class represents more than one possible lexeme, the lexer often saves enough information to reproduce the original lexeme, so that it can be used in semantic analysis.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The parser typically retrieves this information from the lexer and stores it in the abstract syntax tree.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is necessary in order to avoid information loss in the case where numbers may also be valid identifiers.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Tokens are identified based on the specific rules of the lexer.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Some methods used to identify tokens include regular expressions, specific sequences of characters termed a flag, specific separating characters called delimiters, and explicit definition by a dictionary.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Special characters, including punctuation characters, are commonly used by lexers to identify tokens because of their natural use in written and programming languages.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexical analyzer generally does nothing with combinations of tokens, a task left for a parser.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, a typical lexical analyzer recognizes parentheses as tokens but does nothing to ensure that each "(" is matched with a ")".
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] When a lexer feeds tokens to the parser, the representation used is typically an enumerated type, which is a list of number representations.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, "Identifier" can be represented with 0, "Assignment operator" with 1, "Addition operator" with 2, etc.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Tokens are often defined by regular expressions, which are understood by a lexical analyzer generator such as lex, or handcoded equivalent finite-state automata.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The lexical analyzer (generated automatically by a tool like lex or hand-crafted) reads in a stream of characters, identifies the lexemes in the stream, and categorizes them into tokens.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] If the lexer finds an invalid token, it will report an error.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] From there, the interpreted data may be loaded into data structures for general use, interpretation, or compiling.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The specification of a programming language often includes a set of rules, the lexical grammar, which defines the lexical syntax.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The lexical syntax is usually a regular language, with the grammar rules consisting of regular expressions; they define the set of possible character sequences (lexemes) of a token.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexer recognizes strings, and for each kind of string found, the lexical program takes an action, most simply producing a token.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Two important common lexical categories are white space and comments.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] These are also defined in the grammar and processed by the lexer but may be discarded (not producing any tokens) and considered *non-significant*, at most separating two tokens (as in `if x` instead of `ifx`).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] There are two important exceptions to this.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] First, in off-side rule languages that delimit blocks with indenting, initial whitespace is significant, as it determines block structure, and is generally handled at the lexer level; see phrase structure, below.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Secondly, in some uses of lexers, comments and whitespace must be preserved – for examples, a prettyprinter also needs to output the comments and some debugging tools may provide messages to the programmer showing the original source code.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] In the 1960s, notably for ALGOL, whitespace and comments were eliminated as part of the line reconstruction phase (the initial phase of the compiler frontend), but this separate phase has been eliminated and these are now handled by the lexer.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The first stage, the *scanner*, is usually based on a finite-state machine (FSM).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] It has encoded within it information on the possible sequences of characters that can be contained within any of the tokens it handles (individual instances of these character sequences are termed lexemes).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, an *integer* lexeme may contain any sequence of numerical digit characters.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] In some languages, the lexeme creation rules are more complex and may involve backtracking over previously read characters.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, in C, one 'L' character is not enough to distinguish between an identifier that begins with 'L' and a wide-character string literal.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A lexeme, however, is only a string of characters known to be of a certain kind (e.g., a string literal, a sequence of letters).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The second stage of a lexical analyzer, the *evaluator*, goes over the characters of the lexeme to produce a *value* containing relevant information for the parser.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The lexeme's type combined with its value is what properly constitutes a *token*.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The value in the token can be whatever is deemed necessary for the parser to interpret a token of that type.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The evaluator may also suppress a lexeme entirely, concealing it from the parser, which is useful for whitespace and comments.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is practical if the list of tokens is small, but lexers generated by automated tooling as part of a compiler-compiler toolchain are more practical for a larger number of potential tokens.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] These tools generally accept regular expressions that describe the tokens allowed in the input stream.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Each regular expression is associated with a production rule in the lexical grammar of the programming language that evaluates the lexemes matching the regular expression.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] These tools may generate source code that can be compiled and executed or construct a state transition table for a finite-state machine (which is plugged into template code for compiling and executing).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Regular expressions compactly represent patterns that the characters in lexemes might follow.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] For example, for an English-based language, an IDENTIFIER token might be any English alphabetic character or an underscore, followed by any number of instances of ASCII alphanumeric characters and/or underscores.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This could be represented compactly by the string `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z_0-9]*`.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This means "any character a-z, A-Z or _, followed by 0 or more of a-z, A-Z, _ or 0-9".
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] It takes a full parser to recognize such patterns in their full generality.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A parser can push parentheses on a stack and then try to pop them off and see if the stack is empty at the end (see example in the *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* book).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Typically, lexical tokenization occurs at the word level.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, it is sometimes difficult to define what is meant by a "word".
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] In languages that use inter-word spaces (such as most that use the Latin alphabet, and most programming languages), this approach is fairly straightforward.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, even here there are many edge cases such as contractions, hyphenated words, emoticons, and larger constructs such as URIs (which for some purposes may count as single tokens).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A classic example is "New York-based", which a naive tokenizer may break at the space even though the better break is (arguably) at the hyphen.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Tokenization is particularly difficult for languages written in scriptio continua, which exhibit no word boundaries, such as Ancient Greek, Chinese, or Thai.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Agglutinative languages, such as Korean, also make tokenization tasks complicated.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Some ways to address the more difficult problems include developing more complex heuristics, querying a table of common special cases, or fitting the tokens to a language model that identifies collocations in a later processing step.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexers are often generated by a *lexer generator*, analogous to parser generators, and such tools often come together.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The most established is lex, paired with the yacc parser generator, or rather some of their many reimplementations, like flex (often paired with GNU Bison).
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] These generators are a form of domain-specific language, taking in a lexical specification – generally regular expressions with some markup – and emitting a lexer.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] These tools yield very fast development, which is very important in early development, both to get a working lexer and because a language specification may change often.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Further, they often provide advanced features, such as pre- and post-conditions which are hard to program by hand.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, an automatically generated lexer may lack flexibility, and thus may require some manual modification, or an all-manually written lexer.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexer performance is a concern, and optimizing is worthwhile, more so in stable languages where the lexer runs very often (such as C or HTML). lex/flex-generated lexers are reasonably fast, but improvements of two to three times are possible using more tuned generators.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Hand-written lexers are sometimes used, but modern lexer generators produce faster lexers than most hand-coded ones.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The lex/flex family of generators uses a table-driven approach which is much less efficient than the directly coded approach.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] With the latter approach the generator produces an engine that directly jumps to follow-up states via goto statements.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Tools like re2c have proven to produce engines that are between two and three times faster than flex produced engines.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] It is in general difficult to hand-write analyzers that perform better than engines generated by these latter tools.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Lexical analysis mainly segments the input stream of characters into tokens, simply grouping the characters into pieces and categorizing them.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] However, the lexing may be significantly more complex; most simply, lexers may omit tokens or insert added tokens.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Omitting tokens, notably whitespace and comments, is very common when these are not needed by the compiler.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Less commonly, added tokens may be inserted.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is done mainly to group tokens into statements, or statements into blocks, to simplify the parser.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Line continuation is a feature of some languages where a newline is normally a statement terminator.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Most often, ending a line with a backslash (immediately followed by a newline) results in the line being *continued* – the following line is *joined* to the prior line.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is generally done in the lexer: The backslash and newline are discarded, rather than the newline being tokenized.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Examples include bash, other shell scripts and Python.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Many languages use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Most often this is mandatory, but in some languages the semicolon is optional in many contexts.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This is mainly done at the lexer level, where the lexer outputs a semicolon into the token stream, despite one not being present in the input character stream, and is termed *semicolon insertion* or *automatic semicolon insertion*.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] In these cases, semicolons are part of the formal phrase grammar of the language, but may not be found in input text, as they can be inserted by the lexer.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Optional semicolons or other terminators or separators are also sometimes handled at the parser level, notably in the case of trailing commas or semicolons.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is a feature of BCPL and its distant descendant Go, though it is absent in B or C.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is present in JavaScript, though the rules are somewhat complex and much-criticized; to avoid bugs, some recommend always using semicolons, while others use initial semicolons, termed defensive semicolons, at the start of potentially ambiguous statements.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] The off-side rule (blocks determined by indenting) can be implemented in the lexer, as in Python, where increasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting an INDENT token and decreasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting one or more DEDENT tokens.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] These tokens correspond to the opening brace `{` and closing brace `}` in languages that use braces for blocks and means that the phrase grammar does not depend on whether braces or indenting are used.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This requires that the lexer hold state, namely a stack of indent levels, and thus can detect changes in indenting when this changes, and thus the lexical grammar is not context-free: INDENT–DEDENT depend on the contextual information of prior indent levels.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Generally lexical grammars are context-free, or almost so, and thus require no looking back or ahead, or backtracking, which allows a simple, clean, and efficient implementation.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] This also allows simple one-way communication from lexer to parser, without needing any information flowing back to the lexer.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] These examples all only require lexical context, and while they complicate a lexer somewhat, they are invisible to the parser and later phases.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] A more complex example is the lexer hack in C, where the token class of a sequence of characters cannot be determined until the semantic analysis phase since typedef names and variable names are lexically identical but constitute different token classes.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] Thus in the hack, the lexer calls the semantic analyzer (say, symbol table) and checks if the sequence requires a typedef name.
[src:tokenization-nlp/lexical-analysis] In this case, information must flow back not from the parser only, but from the semantic analyzer back to the lexer, which complicates design.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] An ***n*-gram** is a sequence of *n* adjacent symbols in a particular order.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] The symbols may be *n* adjacent letters (including punctuation marks and blanks), syllables, or rarely whole words found in a language dataset; or adjacent phonemes extracted from a speech-recording dataset, or adjacent base pairs extracted from a genome.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] They are collected from a text corpus or speech corpus.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] If Latin numerical prefixes are used, then *n*-gram of size 1 is called a "unigram", size 2 a "bigram" (or, less commonly, a "digram") etc.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] If, instead of the Latin ones, the English cardinal numbers are furtherly used, then they are called "four-gram", "five-gram", etc.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] Similarly, Greek numerical prefixes such as "monomer", "dimer", "trimer", "tetramer", "pentamer", etc., or English cardinal numbers, "one-mer", "two-mer", "three-mer", etc. are used in computational biology for polymers or oligomers of a known size, called *k*-mers.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] When the items are words, n-grams may also be called *shingles*.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] In the context of natural language processing (NLP), the use of *n*-grams allows bag-of-words models to capture information such as word order, which would not be possible in the traditional bag of words setting.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] In 1951, Shannon discussed *n*-gram models of English.
[src:tokenization-nlp/n-gram] Figure 1 shows several example sequences and the corresponding 1-gram, 2-gram and 3-gram sequences.
