[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:tokenization-nlp/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] A **word *n*-gram language model** is a statistical model of language which calculates the probability of the next word in a sequence from a fixed size window of previous words.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] A special case, where *n* = 1, is called a unigram model.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Probability of each word in a sequence is independent from probabilities of other word in the sequence.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Each word's probability in the sequence is equal to the word's probability in an entire document.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] The model consists of units, each treated as one-state finite automata.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Words with their probabilities in a document can be illustrated as follows.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Total mass of word probabilities distributed across the document's vocabulary, is 1.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Unigram models of different documents have different probabilities of words in it.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] The probability distributions from different documents are used to generate hit probabilities for each query.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Documents can be ranked for a query according to the probabilities.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Note that the context of the first *n* – 1 *n*-grams is filled with start-of-sentence markers, typically denoted <s>.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] It is assumed that the probability of observing the *i*th word *wi* (in the context window consisting of the preceding *i* − 1 words) can be approximated by the probability of observing it in the shortened context window consisting of the preceding *n* − 1 words (*n*th-order Markov property).
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] An issue when using *n*-gram language models are out-of-vocabulary (OOV) words.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] They are encountered in computational linguistics and natural language processing when the input includes words which were not present in a system's dictionary or database during its preparation.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] By default, when a language model is estimated, the entire observed vocabulary is used.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] In some cases, it may be necessary to estimate the language model with a specific fixed vocabulary.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] In such a scenario, the *n*-grams in the corpus that contain an out-of-vocabulary word are ignored.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] The *n*-gram probabilities are smoothed over all the words in the vocabulary even if they were not observed.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Nonetheless, it is essential in some cases to explicitly model the probability of out-of-vocabulary words by introducing a special token (e.g.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Out-of-vocabulary words in the corpus are effectively replaced with this special <unk> token before *n*-grams counts are cumulated.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] With this option, it is possible to estimate the transition probabilities of *n*-grams involving out-of-vocabulary words.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] It is also possible to take a more principled approach to the statistics of *n*-grams, modeling similarity as the likelihood that two strings came from the same source directly in terms of a problem in Bayesian inference.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] To choose a value for *n* in an *n*-gram model, it is necessary to find the right trade-off between the stability of the estimate against its appropriateness.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] This means that trigram (i.e. triplets of words) is a common choice with large training corpora (millions of words), whereas a bigram is often used with smaller ones.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] There are problems of balance weight between *infrequent grams* (for example, if a proper name appeared in the training data) and *frequent grams*.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Also, items not seen in the training data will be given a probability of 0.0 without smoothing.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] For unseen but plausible data from a sample, one can introduce pseudocounts.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Pseudocounts are generally motivated on Bayesian grounds.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] In practice it was necessary to *smooth* the probability distributions by also assigning non-zero probabilities to unseen words or *n*-grams.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] The reason is that models derived directly from the *n*-gram frequency counts have severe problems when confronted with any *n*-grams that have not explicitly been seen before – the zero-frequency problem.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Various smoothing methods were used, from simple "add-one" (Laplace) smoothing (assign a count of 1 to unseen *n*-grams; see Rule of succession) to more sophisticated models, such as Good–Turing discounting or back-off models.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Some of these methods are equivalent to assigning a prior distribution to the probabilities of the *n*-grams and using Bayesian inference to compute the resulting posterior *n*-gram probabilities.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] However, the more sophisticated smoothing models were typically not derived in this fashion, but instead through independent considerations.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Syntactic *n*-grams are *n*-grams defined by paths in syntactic dependency or constituent trees rather than the linear structure of the text.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] For example, the sentence "economic news has little effect on financial markets" can be transformed to syntactic *n*-grams following the tree structure of its dependency relations: news-economic, effect-little, effect-on-markets-financial.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Syntactic *n*-grams are intended to reflect syntactic structure more faithfully than linear *n*-grams, and have many of the same applications, especially as features in a vector space model.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Syntactic *n*-grams for certain tasks gives better results than the use of standard *n*-grams, for example, for authorship attribution.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Another type of syntactic *n*-grams are part-of-speech *n*-grams, defined as fixed-length contiguous overlapping subsequences that are extracted from part-of-speech sequences of text.
[src:tokenization-nlp/word-n-gram-language-model] Part-of-speech *n*-grams have several applications, most commonly in information retrieval.
